  issn = {1939-9170},
  doi = {10.2307/2265614},
  abstract = {The relationships between biodiversity and stability were determined for both population and ecosystem traits in a long\textemdash term study of 207 grassland plots. Results demonstrate that biodiversity stabilizes community and ecosystem processes, but not population processes. Specifically, year\textemdash to\textemdash year variability in total aboveground plant community biomass was significantly lower in plots with greater plant species richness both for the entire 11\textemdash yr period and for the nine non\textemdash drought years. The change in total plant community biomass from before the drought to the peak of the drought was also highly dependent on species richness. For all three measures of total community biomass stability, multiple regressions that controlled for covariates showed similar significant relationships between plant diversity and stability. In contrast, year\textemdash to\textemdash year variability in species abundances was not stabilized by plant species richness for either all years or non\textemdash drought years. This difference between species vs. community biomass likely results from interspecific competition. When climatic variations harm some species, unharmed competitors increase. Such compensatory increases stabilize total community biomass, but cause species abundances to be more variable. These results support both the predictions of Robert May concerning the effects of diversity on population stability and the diversity\textemdash stability hypothesis as applied to community and ecosystem processes, thus helping to reconcile a long\textemdash standing dispute.},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {biodiversity,climatic variability,compensation,competition,diversity-stability hypothesis,drought,grasslands,prairie,primary productivity,savanna,stability},
  annotation = {\_eprint: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/pdf/10.2307/2265614},
